english:
  title: 'On Choi Ja-go''s Teaching: The Gate'
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When we erect gates to fortify a nation, invaders cannot breach its defenses. When we maintain reverence to strengthen our resolve, external desires cannot sway us. Though the scale differs—great and small—the principle of guardianship remains one.

    Yet a nation cannot rely on gates and walls alone; it must strengthen its foundation. The Qin built their walls upon mountains and their moats from rivers—their fortifications seemed impregnable. Yet when sentries at Hangu Gate cried out once, all was lost. Can such barriers truly be trusted? We learn then that fortress walls, however formidable, are not what we should prize. What matters is securing the root and bringing peace to the people. The Book of History tells us: "The people are the nation's foundation; when the root is firm, the state finds peace."

    Reflect upon this in your own person: the heart, when grasped, endures; when released, perishes. In the heart's movements lies a distinction between good and evil—we must not fail to make reverence our master, enriching the good and expunging the evil. The ancients say that sincere intention is the gate between good and evil. Whoever passes through this gate without self-deception, with genuine shame at falsehood, guards it truly. From this, the heart finds rectitude, the person finds cultivation, and the state and world find order and peace.

    Thus the cultivated person, in stillness, applies ceaseless work of preserving and nurturing; in motion, exhausts all effort in examination and restraint. Making reverence the master of practice, never pausing—then heaven's principle abides eternally, human desire naturally dissolves. Whether riches or poverty, life or death, honor or disgrace alternate before us, the will grows ever firmer. No worldly thing can move what lies within.

    Without this, though outer deportment gleams with propriety, few remain unmoved when facing profit and harm. Thus the polish of propriety is not reverence; fortress walls are not true strength. Only when root and branch are both perfected, inner cultivation and outer practice united, do we achieve completion.

    My friend, the great Minister Choi, bears the name Gate and the courtesy name Steadfast-Foundation. Should he embody this in himself and extend it to his nation, then his name and title will bear no shame.
  footnotes:
    - 'Hangu Gate (函谷關): A famous strategic pass during China''s Warring States period, symbolizing the failure of external defenses when internal discipline wavers.'
    - 'The Book of History (書經): A classical Chinese text containing foundational Confucian teachings on governance and virtue.'
    - The distinction between Heaven's Principle (天理) and Human Desire (人欲) reflects core Neo-Confucian philosophy, particularly the school of Zhu Xi.
    - Choi Ja-go's name (關/子固) means 'Gate' and 'Steadfast Foundation,' making him a living embodiment of the essay's central metaphor about fortification through inner virtue.
